7.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=discovery1>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/9/02 10:09 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   What's needed to build an Orion?</span><hr size=1> <br>
<br>
  I have two questions:<br>
     1. What types of materials are needed to build an Orion<br>
     2. Are they available in the necessary quantities on the Moon<br>
<br>
  You can probably see where this is going, although it would be very difficult to build the infrastructure required.  <br>
<br>
Discovery 1 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/10/02 10:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What's needed to build an Orion?</span><hr size=1> An Orion would be built out of the same type material as a modern<br>
Naval warship.  Steel, aluminium, iron, really heavy sturdy stuff.<br>
<br>
It would almost take an Orion to place the needed infrastructure on<br>
the moon to build an Orion. Sort of like 'which came first, the<br>
chicken or the egg?' type problem.<br>
<br>
May be easier to 'harvest' a near earth asteroid for the needed<br>
material.  But you would still need a shipyard size construction site<br>
on orbit to process the raw material etc.  Not an easy task to place<br>
that much infrastructure on orbit with conventional rocket technology.<br>
Maybe if they get that space elevator working that would solve the<br>
first problem, cheap access to space.<br>
<br>
Of course this all depends on the size of the finished product.  An<br>
Orion scales up better than it scales down so I tend to support a<br>
really big Orion.  I'm talking battleship size here.<br>
<br>
Battlestar Orion! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ujohnfraz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://members.hometown.aol.com/_ht_a/naturyl/images/YinYangsblack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 83<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/10/02 3:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What's needed to build an Orion?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; May be easier to 'harvest' a near earth asteroid<br>
for the needed material.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Definitely. Easier in several ways:<br>
 Less delta-V needed to get there (less total velocity change, less rocketry overall) This is the big one. What this means is that the same misson leaving Earth could get to an asteroid sooner, or carry more cargo, or be smaller overall for the same cargo. It also means that smaller rockets wil be needed to &quot;Dock&quot; with an asteroid, than to land on the Moon. These will be more efficient and safer than the big landing rockets.<br>
<br>
 One of the main points in favor of the asteroids is the quality of resources there. They call the Moon the slag pile of the solar system: Lunar ores are about what an asteroid miner would throw away as not economical to process further. As well, you'll find water &amp; other process chemicals at an asteroid, instead of having to get it from Earth. For every ton of finished metals from Lunar ores, you'll need 7 times the finished mass of water &amp; process chemicals.<br>
 You get all of it at an asteroid, along with free solar energy -not having to drag a nuclear plant to the Moon, and soft-land it.<br>
<br>
 Finally, remember that in space, you don't have to have a place to build things on, or to &quot;take off from&quot;. Gathering parts for construction in free space is easy, as is gently and efficiently taking the ship out. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=discovery1>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/10/02 3:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What's needed to build an Orion?</span><hr size=1> <br>
<br>
How heavy would be the refinery be? What would it be made of? Carbon composites? On a note related to the star latter, I thought that the space station which would crown it might serve as an &quot;Orionyard.&quot; Oh, and thanks of replying<br>
