<br>
  I have another question:<br>
    What would be the source of electricity on an Orion? Fuel cells? A nuclear reactor? But, I do know that nuclear weapons would be used as fuel, of course.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=cattlecar>cattlecar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 31<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/10/02 9:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What's needed to build an Orion?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> What would be the source of electricity on an Orion? Fuel cells? A nuclear reactor? But, I do know that nuclear<br>
weapons would be used as fuel, of course.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Most definitely a nuclear reator would be present on larger Orions, a<br>
smaller type Orion, say the 10 meter pusher plate Saturn V boosted<br>
manned Mars mission solar only 'may' work.  But a reactor would be<br>
preferred for it's massive power supply.  Deep Space missions to the<br>
outer planets, Jupiter and beyond, would require a nuclear reactor or<br>
two on board.<br>
<br>
Consider a modern nuclear submarine in design specs, size, crew<br>
compliment, power source, etc. when thinking of a medium size Orion. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1128<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/10/02 11:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What's needed to build an Orion?</span><hr size=1> Electricity requirements would be quite small. The Nasa image of a modern Orion depicts solar panels on the outside. This would be sufficient for communications, life support and computers. Remember that even a small Orion would have no difficulty in carrying very large panels. Far larger than the ISS and several times more output, since the ISS panels are already quite old.<br>
A nuclear reactor would be better if you take your ship to the outer planets or the darkside of any body. Larger ships would use far more power. Solariums, heated swimming pools and jacuzzis, coridoor lighting, bowling alley pin straighteners, laser asteroid defenses, disco music etc. as the fastest way of getting from A to B the Orion will some day be the concorde of the spaceways. Full of business class suites for the rich and famous who expect the best. <br>
<br>
Brittney Speers wont be taking an ion drive to Titan. Assuming she is still famous when space is opened up. <p>~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
<br>Nuclear power is the next logical step for serious space travel. The technology required to colonise the solar system exists now!

<br><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace">NUCLEARSPACE</a>
</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=discovery1>Discovery 1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/13/02 5:45 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=88.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nsmessageboard/ezboard/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What's needed to build an Orion?</span><hr size=1> I know it's a little late to respond to cattlecar's first comment, but I beg to differ. I maintain that an Orion would be made out of various plastics. This is because:<br>
<br>
1: plastics are lighter than metals, mostly<br>
